The @naic takes the position that #Bitcoin is a non-admitted asset. So all of the above is not in play b/c the assets held in #Bitcoin do not qualify as an admitted asset for calculations of solvency & various ratios.

The @naic holds considerable sway over state insurance depts.

This means that a #Bitcoin crash - even if for a limited time - might render an insurance carrier insolvent regardless of underwriting profitability.

But wait! There is more!

If $100 of #Bitcoin is impaired to $50 then the carrier may be considered insolvent by a regulator and need to get more surplus. Or the premium to surplus ratio may be negative and require raising rates to make up the difference.

Intangible assets are "impaired" by accountants when their price falls. There is no mechanism in accounting to mark-to-market when an intangible asset's value increases. 

Thus, #Bitcoin only depreciates on an insurance carrier's balance sheet. Never goes up.

Federal courts have unanimously held that #cryptocurrency - specifically #Bitcoin constitutes both #money and #currency. Under US GAAP & IFRS, currency is treated as cash. 

However, that is not how the @AICPA want to treat #Bitcoin.

Adoption of #Bitcoin by insurance carriers as part of their reserves would reduce price variance, increase usage as a medium of exchange, and further the proliferation of #cryptocurrency in general. The @AICPA & the @SECGov have nonsensical accounting positions precluding this.
